<DOC><DOCNO> AP880521-0169 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 2124EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-France-Mitterrand     05-21 0188</FIRST><SECOND>AM-France-Mitterrand,0192</SECOND><HEAD>Re-elected President Begins Second Term</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Francois Mitterrand began his secondseven-year term Saturday, promising to formulate policy aimed atuniting fellow Socialists with non-Socialists.   Speaking during a 20-minute inauguration ceremony, Mitterrandsaid his May 8 re-election, in which he defeated conservativeJacques Chirac, who then resigned as premier, ``was not the goodones winning over the bad ones, nor the other way around.''   He called on French people to work together ``so that theprinciple of hope might triumph over the compulsions of fear andconfrontation.''   Mitterrand, 71, has called legislative elections for June 5,with runoffs June 12, in which Socialists backing new PremierMichel Rocard are expected to win a large majority in the 577-setNational Assembly.   Rocard and his Cabinet ministers and other top officials wereamong about 150 people attending the ceremony in the glitteringSalle des Fetes (Festival Hall) of the presidential Elysee Palace.Prominent guests included author Marguerite Duras and actor GerardDepardieu.   The proceedings were televised nationwide. Schoolchildren, whonormally attend classes for a half-day on Saturdays, were given aholiday for the occasion.</TEXT></DOC>